00:01:29.610 --> 00:01:29.780
GEORGE TILLMAN: Yeah

00:01:29.780 --> 00:01:32.620
SPEAKER: So tell me what about
this book and this screenplay

00:01:32.620 --> 00:01:33.510
drew you to it.

00:01:33.510 --> 00:01:35.670
Why did you want to tell
this story specifically?

00:01:35.670 --> 00:01:36.330
GEORGE TILLMAN:
Yeah, what I really

00:01:36.330 --> 00:01:38.370
love about it was
it was specifically

00:01:38.370 --> 00:01:41.639
about the culture, about this
young girl and her family.

00:01:41.639 --> 00:01:43.680
You know, the ideal of
navigating between the two

00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:44.670
worlds.

00:01:44.670 --> 00:01:48.240
So the ideal of her
struggling, and then

00:01:48.240 --> 00:01:50.080
that being a compromised
when she witnessed

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:52.320
the shooting of her
best friend, I just

00:01:52.320 --> 00:01:54.990
thought that was an
interesting character arc.

00:01:54.990 --> 00:01:58.230
But what I love is how the
family's always center.

00:01:58.230 --> 00:02:01.890
And no matter tough
things get, no matter

00:02:01.890 --> 00:02:06.390
how people in the neighborhood
tell her not to say anything

00:02:06.390 --> 00:02:09.060
about this shooting,
or how much pressure

00:02:09.060 --> 00:02:11.280
she feels from the
police department,

00:02:11.280 --> 00:02:14.430
and how much pressure she
feels from her white friends,

00:02:14.430 --> 00:02:17.340
her white private
school, she just pushes,

00:02:17.340 --> 00:02:19.360
and it makes the film
has this emotional roller

00:02:19.360 --> 00:02:21.990
coaster, where you're going
through all these emotions.

00:02:21.990 --> 00:02:24.494
That's what I really
imagined, envisioned

00:02:24.494 --> 00:02:26.910
for the movie when I talked
to Angie, because her book was

00:02:26.910 --> 00:02:28.110
very amazing.

00:02:28.110 --> 00:02:30.120
But what I really love is how--

00:02:30.120 --> 00:02:33.990
which I find really
significant--

00:02:33.990 --> 00:02:37.260
is that you can tell a movie
about this specific culture,

00:02:37.260 --> 00:02:38.859
but it could be for everyone.

00:02:38.859 --> 00:02:40.650
And you can do it in
a way where you're not

00:02:40.650 --> 00:02:42.675
compromising who we are.

00:02:42.675 --> 00:02:43.800
And I think that's the key.

00:02:43.800 --> 00:02:44.610
SPEAKER: Absolutely.

00:02:44.610 --> 00:02:46.470
And that's one of the things
that was the most beautiful

00:02:46.470 --> 00:02:46.980
about it.

00:02:46.980 --> 00:02:48.540
I mean, it's the
kind of movie that

00:02:48.540 --> 00:02:50.640
can speak to a
range of audiences

00:02:50.640 --> 00:02:52.770
and really welcomes them
in with open arms, which

00:02:52.770 --> 00:02:55.710
is so incredible and
hard to do, I think.

00:02:55.710 --> 00:02:59.340
So Amandla, for you, what
brought you to this movie?

00:02:59.340 --> 00:03:01.350
So I hear that
you signed on even

00:03:01.350 --> 00:03:02.700
before the book was published.

00:03:02.700 --> 00:03:05.042
You were all in, ready to go.

00:03:05.042 --> 00:03:05.750
This was for you.

00:03:05.750 --> 00:03:06.269
[LAUGHING]

00:03:06.269 --> 00:03:07.560
How did you make that decision?

00:03:07.560 --> 00:03:09.881
What connected you
to Starr's story?

00:03:09.881 --> 00:03:11.880
AMANDLA STENBERG: What
connected me to the story

00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:14.130
was the book by Angie Thomas.

00:03:14.130 --> 00:03:16.680
And if you haven't read it, I
highly recommend that you do,

00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:18.300
because it is so beautiful.

00:03:18.300 --> 00:03:19.352
SPEAKER: Second that.

00:03:19.352 --> 00:03:20.310
AMANDLA STENBERG: Yeah.

00:03:20.310 --> 00:03:22.200
I was immediately
just blown away

00:03:22.200 --> 00:03:25.830
by this story and the
power that it had in

00:03:25.830 --> 00:03:30.780
depicting a nuanced
experience of blackness

00:03:30.780 --> 00:03:32.730
in a contemporary world.

00:03:32.730 --> 00:03:34.530
I feel like not
often are we afforded

00:03:34.530 --> 00:03:36.476
those sorts of representations.

00:03:36.476 --> 00:03:38.100
And so it was really
exhilarating to me

00:03:38.100 --> 00:03:41.700
to see this girl who was
code switching, you know,

00:03:41.700 --> 00:03:43.350
who is presenting
herself differently

00:03:43.350 --> 00:03:44.490
in different spaces.

00:03:44.490 --> 00:03:45.410
SPEAKER: Right.

00:03:45.410 --> 00:03:47.910
AMANDLA STENBERG: And then the
way in which she's galvanized

00:03:47.910 --> 00:03:51.540
towards activism because of
these really tragic events

00:03:51.540 --> 00:03:54.780
that we've often
become desensitized to.

00:03:54.780 --> 00:03:58.390
So to see those placed
in a personal narrative,

00:03:58.390 --> 00:04:02.460
and to understand the power of
instilling empathy in people

00:04:02.460 --> 00:04:05.520
through that, that's what
really drew me to it.

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:08.360
SPEAKER: And so you
mentioned code switching.

00:04:08.360 --> 00:04:11.036
And that's a term that's kind of
gaining more and more attention

00:04:11.036 --> 00:04:12.660
as people are trying
to understand what

00:04:12.660 --> 00:04:15.540
it is to be a person
of color in two

00:04:15.540 --> 00:04:18.870
different spaces in the world,
a white space and a black space.

00:04:18.870 --> 00:04:20.459
Can you explain
a little bit more

00:04:20.459 --> 00:04:22.860
about that, and how
Starr sees herself

00:04:22.860 --> 00:04:25.140
code switching in the movie,
the specific situations

00:04:25.140 --> 00:04:28.392
that she feels that she
needs to make that change?

00:04:28.392 --> 00:04:29.600
AMANDLA STENBERG: Yeah, sure.

00:04:29.600 --> 00:04:35.040
So code switching
is entering spaces

00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:38.280
that you're not necessarily
fully accepted into,

00:04:38.280 --> 00:04:41.430
and so understanding that the
way that you present yourself

00:04:41.430 --> 00:04:44.460
in that space might be a
little different from how

00:04:44.460 --> 00:04:46.890
you are in your most
authentic environment,

00:04:46.890 --> 00:04:50.430
because you understand
that if you present

00:04:50.430 --> 00:04:54.420
as authentically as
you are, it could

00:04:54.420 --> 00:04:57.390
be detrimental to your
success, unfortunately,

00:04:57.390 --> 00:05:01.440
or you could be further
alienated or isolated, which is

00:05:01.440 --> 00:05:03.349
something that everyone does.

00:05:03.349 --> 00:05:04.890
You know, when you're
at home, you're

00:05:04.890 --> 00:05:06.810
probably a little
different than who

00:05:06.810 --> 00:05:09.450
you are at work or at school.

00:05:09.450 --> 00:05:12.260
But Starr is really
caught in this dichotomy--

00:05:12.260 --> 00:05:16.340
which I actually
experienced as well--

00:05:16.340 --> 00:05:18.200
of growing up in a
neighborhood that

00:05:18.200 --> 00:05:22.550
is black and has a lot less
privilege than the neighborhood

00:05:22.550 --> 00:05:24.560
that the kids at
her school are from,

00:05:24.560 --> 00:05:28.520
because she goes to this school
an hour and half across town

00:05:28.520 --> 00:05:29.570
that's mostly white.

00:05:29.570 --> 00:05:32.270
And so she's one of the
only black students there,

00:05:32.270 --> 00:05:36.650
and she does a lot of
self-policing because she knows

00:05:36.650 --> 00:05:39.770
that these kids don't understand
her experience of blackness,

00:05:39.770 --> 00:05:43.760
don't understand her community,
or who she is, or her culture.

00:05:43.760 --> 00:05:47.240
And so she figures out how
to adjust to that environment

00:05:47.240 --> 00:05:48.890
in order to be more accepted.

00:05:48.890 --> 00:05:49.850
SPEAKER: Absolutely.

00:05:49.850 --> 00:05:52.516
AMANDLA STENBERG: And so the way
that that manifests in the film

00:05:52.516 --> 00:05:56.600
is she has Starr Version
1 and Starr Version 2.

00:05:56.600 --> 00:06:00.610
And when I first read it in
the book, it really just--

00:06:00.610 --> 00:06:02.270
it registered in a
way that I had never

00:06:02.270 --> 00:06:06.620
seen it depicted, like in any
sort of piece of media before.

00:06:06.620 --> 00:06:09.380
Whereas Starr describes
the experience

00:06:09.380 --> 00:06:13.850
of feeling and hearing
your voice change.

00:06:13.850 --> 00:06:18.110
When you enter a space that
you're not most comfortable in,

00:06:18.110 --> 00:06:21.950
or at least when you enter
a white space in which you

00:06:21.950 --> 00:06:25.830
understand that your blackness
will not be understood--

00:06:25.830 --> 00:06:26.870
SPEAKER: Right, right.

00:06:26.870 --> 00:06:29.210
AMANDLA STENBERG: So I
really connected to that,

00:06:29.210 --> 00:06:35.330
and this whole idea of Starr
being kind of canonized by her

00:06:35.330 --> 00:06:39.200
peers at school as an
accessible black girl,

00:06:39.200 --> 00:06:42.620
as a nonthreatening
black girl, as a

00:06:42.620 --> 00:06:44.800
not-like-other-black-people
black girl

00:06:44.800 --> 00:06:45.620
SPEAKER: Oh, Starr,
you're different.

00:06:45.620 --> 00:06:47.078
AMANDLA STENBERG:
You're different.

00:06:47.078 --> 00:06:48.650
You're not like them.

00:06:48.650 --> 00:06:50.690
Which is just so
kind of invalidating

00:06:50.690 --> 00:06:54.590
and simplifies our
existence in a way

00:06:54.590 --> 00:06:55.890
that's really detrimental.

00:06:55.890 --> 00:06:58.940
So it was so
exhilarating to me to see

00:06:58.940 --> 00:07:02.180
a portrayal of a black
girl that was actually

00:07:02.180 --> 00:07:04.220
reflective of our
experiences and that

00:07:04.220 --> 00:07:09.830
was really expansive and all
encompassing and multifaceted.

00:07:09.830 --> 00:07:12.620
Because oftentimes,
you know, we're

00:07:12.620 --> 00:07:14.660
only given a certain
amount of tropes

00:07:14.660 --> 00:07:16.040
that we're allowed to play.

00:07:16.040 --> 00:07:17.240
SPEAKER: It's a
little box sometimes.

00:07:17.240 --> 00:07:18.310
AMANDLA STENBERG:
There's a little box.

00:07:18.310 --> 00:07:18.809
Yeah.

00:07:18.809 --> 00:07:21.260
We can play the humor.

00:07:21.260 --> 00:07:23.387
We can play the pain.

00:07:23.387 --> 00:07:23.970
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:07:23.970 --> 00:07:25.511
AMANDLA STENBERG:
But not often is it

00:07:25.511 --> 00:07:28.070
that we get to be
everything, and so that's

00:07:28.070 --> 00:07:31.697
what was so exhilarating
about reading this character.

00:07:31.697 --> 00:07:33.530
You're right, in the
unpublished manuscript.

00:07:33.530 --> 00:07:35.570
It wasn't out yet.

00:07:35.570 --> 00:07:38.120
But it was floating
around, because people

00:07:38.120 --> 00:07:39.800
were so excited about it.

00:07:39.800 --> 00:07:42.020
And I attached really early on.

00:07:42.020 --> 00:07:43.760
SPEAKER: Your heart
latched on, for sure.

00:07:43.760 --> 00:07:45.020
AMANDLA STENBERG: My heart
latched on for dear life.

00:07:45.020 --> 00:07:45.520
SPEAKER: Which is great.

00:07:45.520 --> 00:07:47.395
That says something
about the work, for sure.

00:07:47.395 --> 00:07:48.464
AMANDLA STENBERG: Yeah.

00:07:48.464 --> 00:07:50.380
Another thing that I
kind of want to discuss--

00:07:50.380 --> 00:07:52.220
I mean, it's super,
super timely.

00:07:52.220 --> 00:07:55.100
Obviously, police
brutality is on the top

00:07:55.100 --> 00:07:58.100
of mind for so many people,
and especially here in Chicago

00:07:58.100 --> 00:08:00.590
with the case of Laquan
McDonald, Jason Van Dyke just

00:08:00.590 --> 00:08:03.290
being convicted for his murder.

00:08:03.290 --> 00:08:05.750
What is the importance
of a movie like this,

00:08:05.750 --> 00:08:06.650
landing at this time?

00:08:06.650 --> 00:08:07.760
You know, there's
never a right time

00:08:07.760 --> 00:08:09.330
to talk about the hard things.

00:08:09.330 --> 00:08:13.520
But it seems like this is
almost healing in a way,

00:08:13.520 --> 00:08:15.920
for this movie to happen
right now, as some things are

00:08:15.920 --> 00:08:16.764
changing in America.

00:08:16.764 --> 00:08:17.680
GEORGE TILLMAN: Mm-hm.

00:08:17.680 --> 00:08:18.440
Yeah.

00:08:18.440 --> 00:08:22.880
Yeah, I just felt
like, you know,

00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:28.380
I was just telling Amandla, like
we were in Atlanta last week,

00:08:28.380 --> 00:08:30.800
and we finished this screening,
and someone tapped me

00:08:30.800 --> 00:08:33.470
on my shoulder, and I
turned around, and asked,

00:08:33.470 --> 00:08:34.460
can we take a picture?

00:08:34.460 --> 00:08:35.720
And I was like, yeah,
we can take a picture.

00:08:35.720 --> 00:08:37.970
And they were like, thank
you so much for the movie.

00:08:37.970 --> 00:08:40.309
And they said, we're the
family of Emmett Till.

00:08:40.309 --> 00:08:44.600
And I was like, you know,
just kind of blowing me away.

00:08:44.600 --> 00:08:47.760
It was the whole family,
like six of them.

00:08:47.760 --> 00:08:51.440
And I just think back to Emmett
Till, being here from Chicago,

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:53.060
going down to Mississippi.

00:08:53.060 --> 00:08:55.910
You know, he had sort
of the talk early,

00:08:55.910 --> 00:08:58.930
because his mom was telling him
how to act down in Mississippi,

00:08:58.930 --> 00:09:01.400
and how to conduct yourself is
a little different from down

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:02.000
there.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.700
So that talk is something that
you progress over the years.

00:09:04.700 --> 00:09:07.040
It probably was started
through slavery, you know,

00:09:07.040 --> 00:09:10.670
when we were free, and how do
you act around certain people?

00:09:10.670 --> 00:09:14.150
So I just felt like it was very
important for other cultures

00:09:14.150 --> 00:09:18.440
to be able to recognize and see
that the talk to some people

00:09:18.440 --> 00:09:19.820
is like the birds and the bees.

00:09:19.820 --> 00:09:22.370
But for us, for
African-Americans, or people

00:09:22.370 --> 00:09:24.570
of color, it's a difference.

00:09:24.570 --> 00:09:28.670
So in a young girl like
Starr, just have to navigate

00:09:28.670 --> 00:09:29.970
and keep pushing through.

00:09:29.970 --> 00:09:32.030
She's very much of
the world, and know

00:09:32.030 --> 00:09:35.510
how to interact and know how
to move inside her [INAUDIBLE]

00:09:35.510 --> 00:09:36.480
world.

00:09:36.480 --> 00:09:38.840
But she has another-- we
have these other things

00:09:38.840 --> 00:09:40.060
almost as well.

00:09:40.060 --> 00:09:42.560
So a lot of that is just to let
people, as Angie was saying,

00:09:42.560 --> 00:09:46.070
who wrote the book, is to have
empathy what people go through,

00:09:46.070 --> 00:09:49.550
and also recognizing how
did these things happen.

00:09:49.550 --> 00:09:53.390
And the shooting of the cop, why
did he react the way he react?

00:09:53.390 --> 00:09:54.560
We talked about that.

00:09:54.560 --> 00:09:57.530
And we see it from a black
cop perspective with Common.

00:09:57.530 --> 00:09:59.240
And we'll see,
sometimes, there's not

00:09:59.240 --> 00:10:00.610
that much of a difference.

00:10:00.610 --> 00:10:03.380
So when you think about that,
it has to be the system.

00:10:03.380 --> 00:10:04.220
The system.

00:10:04.220 --> 00:10:06.230
How do they teach cops?

00:10:06.230 --> 00:10:07.310
Who were in charge?

00:10:07.310 --> 00:10:09.495
Who are the leaders
inside those departments?

00:10:09.495 --> 00:10:11.340
And we don't condemn.

00:10:11.340 --> 00:10:14.130
We just show what
the reality is,

00:10:14.130 --> 00:10:16.014
so we can cause conversation.

00:10:16.014 --> 00:10:18.180
SPEAKER: I thought Common's
character, Uncle Carlos,

00:10:18.180 --> 00:10:19.429
was so unique.

00:10:19.429 --> 00:10:20.970
Like you were saying,
you don't often

00:10:20.970 --> 00:10:23.580
get the perspective
of a black cop.

00:10:23.580 --> 00:10:26.460
I mean, it's such an
interesting situation

00:10:26.460 --> 00:10:29.640
to be in where you see what
the people are going through.

00:10:29.640 --> 00:10:30.265
You understand.

00:10:30.265 --> 00:10:31.390
You're part of the culture.

00:10:31.390 --> 00:10:33.420
And then, also being
kind of on the other side

00:10:33.420 --> 00:10:35.610
of, these are your coworkers,
these are your colleagues,

00:10:35.610 --> 00:10:36.450
and how do you speak up.

00:10:36.450 --> 00:10:36.870
So--

00:10:36.870 --> 00:10:37.620
GEORGE TILLMAN: Yeah.

00:10:37.620 --> 00:10:39.180
SPEAKER: He's so
nuanced in that way.

00:10:39.180 --> 00:10:39.850
GEORGE TILLMAN: Yeah.

00:10:39.850 --> 00:10:40.470
And it's true.

00:10:40.470 --> 00:10:43.030
I mean, let's say all
of us in this room,

00:10:43.030 --> 00:10:44.670
we all have it inside of us.

00:10:44.670 --> 00:10:48.426
I mean, let's just take
Common's character, myself, like

00:10:48.426 --> 00:10:50.550
as an African American man,
and it's a conversation

00:10:50.550 --> 00:10:52.600
that we have had in rehearsals.

00:10:52.600 --> 00:10:55.350
If I'm walking on the
south side of Chicago,

00:10:55.350 --> 00:10:58.090
if I'm by myself,
African American man,

00:10:58.090 --> 00:11:00.780
and if I see three African
American guys walking

00:11:00.780 --> 00:11:03.075
on the other side of street,
and they walk over here,

00:11:03.075 --> 00:11:04.820
I'm gonna think something's up.

00:11:04.820 --> 00:11:06.690
I'm gonna move over
across the street.

00:11:06.690 --> 00:11:08.460
So that's that own
internal racism

00:11:08.460 --> 00:11:10.849
that I have within myself
within my own culture.

00:11:10.849 --> 00:11:11.890
So that has to be broken.

00:11:11.890 --> 00:11:14.750
That's what Common realizes
when this young girl, Starr,

00:11:14.750 --> 00:11:16.380
confronts him.

00:11:16.380 --> 00:11:18.930
And those are the
kind of dialogues

00:11:18.930 --> 00:11:20.125
that the movie brings up.

00:11:20.125 --> 00:11:20.750
SPEAKER: Right.

00:11:20.750 --> 00:11:21.330
GEORGE TILLMAN: You
know what I mean?

00:11:21.330 --> 00:11:22.102
On both sides.

00:11:22.102 --> 00:11:23.560
SPEAKER: And it's
beautifully done.

00:11:23.560 --> 00:11:26.250
AMANDLA STENBERG: I think
Angie's intention with the book

00:11:26.250 --> 00:11:29.850
was to present these
topics and these issues

00:11:29.850 --> 00:11:35.610
in a way that was inclusive of
different perspectives, that

00:11:35.610 --> 00:11:39.390
didn't further perpetuate a
divisiveness, that grounded it

00:11:39.390 --> 00:11:40.930
in humanity.

00:11:40.930 --> 00:11:44.280
And like, we always get
asked about the timeliness

00:11:44.280 --> 00:11:46.020
of this project.

00:11:46.020 --> 00:11:48.542
The thing is, it's been
timely for a really long time.

00:11:48.542 --> 00:11:49.500
SPEAKER: Always timely.

00:11:49.500 --> 00:11:51.583
AMANDLA STENBERG: And
unfortunately, will probably

00:11:51.583 --> 00:11:53.610
be timely for a while.

00:11:53.610 --> 00:11:56.010
But we always get asked
this also really interesting

00:11:56.010 --> 00:11:56.710
question.

00:11:56.710 --> 00:11:59.700
And I think last night, we
got asked it, which was,

00:11:59.700 --> 00:12:03.770
what is the role of an
artist in social movements?

00:12:03.770 --> 00:12:07.020
Like, what is the
role of the filmmaker?

00:12:07.020 --> 00:12:09.090
You know, when is
it time to make art,

00:12:09.090 --> 00:12:12.480
and then when is it time
to get up and go out

00:12:12.480 --> 00:12:14.420
in the streets in protest?

00:12:14.420 --> 00:12:17.070
And I think they're
so interconnected,

00:12:17.070 --> 00:12:20.479
and both are so invaluable.

00:12:20.479 --> 00:12:22.020
SPEAKER: They work
off of each other.

00:12:22.020 --> 00:12:22.070
AMANDLA STENBERG: Yeah.

00:12:22.070 --> 00:12:24.403
And when they work off of
each other, as you know, like,

00:12:24.403 --> 00:12:27.750
art has always been one of
the driving forces or conduits

00:12:27.750 --> 00:12:29.520
for social movements.

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:30.400
SPEAKER: Absolutely

00:12:30.400 --> 00:12:31.983
AMANDLA STENBERG:
Like they, you know,

00:12:31.983 --> 00:12:34.540
have like a really beautiful
symbiotic relationship.

00:12:34.540 --> 00:12:38.190
And so, I think that was the
driving force behind this

00:12:38.190 --> 00:12:40.410
piece, is to make
something that,

00:12:40.410 --> 00:12:45.000
in the midst of what feels like
chaos and what feels like times

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:49.690
in which things are postulated
as so black and white,

00:12:49.690 --> 00:12:55.080
wrong versus right, me versus
you, winner versus loser,

00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:57.870
I think it was-- it felt
important to create something

00:12:57.870 --> 00:13:01.950
that explored it in a way that
would ground us and what makes

00:13:01.950 --> 00:13:07.200
us most human, and understand
that every single experience is

00:13:07.200 --> 00:13:11.160
multifaceted and requires--

00:13:11.160 --> 00:13:14.070
in order for there to be
any sort of movement made

00:13:14.070 --> 00:13:18.180
or any progress made,
you have to consider

00:13:18.180 --> 00:13:21.725
even your enemy in a way
that is not one-dimensional.

00:13:21.725 --> 00:13:22.350
SPEAKER: Right.

00:13:22.350 --> 00:13:23.760
And it also comes
down to empathy,

00:13:23.760 --> 00:13:24.810
like you were saying before.

00:13:24.810 --> 00:13:25.290
AMANDLA STENBERG: And empathy.

00:13:25.290 --> 00:13:27.300
SPEAKER: Just being able
to understand and look

00:13:27.300 --> 00:13:29.880
at another side or perspective.

00:13:29.880 --> 00:13:31.964
You mentioned the
humanity in this.

00:13:31.964 --> 00:13:33.880
You know, there's so
much going on this movie.

00:13:33.880 --> 00:13:34.800
There are so many themes.

00:13:34.800 --> 00:13:37.008
But one of the things that
I found really interesting

00:13:37.008 --> 00:13:39.830
is your portrayal
of the black family.

00:13:39.830 --> 00:13:41.040
Right?

00:13:41.040 --> 00:13:42.660
You don't get a
lot of that in TV.

00:13:42.660 --> 00:13:45.090
I mean, we're starting to
get there a little bit more

00:13:45.090 --> 00:13:48.510
with shows like "Blackish,"
and we're normalizing it.

00:13:48.510 --> 00:13:51.000
But Maverick is such an
interesting character as well,

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:56.310
because he is this father who is
so complex, and he's done time,

00:13:56.310 --> 00:13:58.160
and it wasn't
necessarily his fault,

00:13:58.160 --> 00:14:01.381
but he's coming from this
one life that he had before,

00:14:01.381 --> 00:14:03.630
and it's kind of completely
switching into a new role,

00:14:03.630 --> 00:14:06.300
and he's being a father.

00:14:06.300 --> 00:14:09.600
I'm interested to know, what was
the most important thing to you

00:14:09.600 --> 00:14:12.930
when you were portraying black
masculinity and fatherhood,

00:14:12.930 --> 00:14:15.085
and the home in this movie?

00:14:15.085 --> 00:14:15.960
GEORGE TILLMAN: Yeah.

00:14:15.960 --> 00:14:19.290
One of the things that
I loved, that, you know,

00:14:19.290 --> 00:14:22.950
the perspective of having
a father in a movie

00:14:22.950 --> 00:14:25.920
like this-- because
when I look back,

00:14:25.920 --> 00:14:28.600
I've been making films for a
little bit, since the '90s.

00:14:28.600 --> 00:14:29.940
SPEAKER: Little bit.

00:14:29.940 --> 00:14:31.920
GEORGE TILLMAN: So when
you look back at it,

00:14:31.920 --> 00:14:35.580
I say some of the African
American characters, films

00:14:35.580 --> 00:14:38.160
that have African American
characters in it, 80%,

00:14:38.160 --> 00:14:41.130
70% of them don't have a
father figure in the household.

00:14:41.130 --> 00:14:42.730
It's always a single parent.

00:14:42.730 --> 00:14:45.780
And that's not the case in the
neighborhood that I grew up in.

00:14:45.780 --> 00:14:48.649
I had fathers next to me, to
the left or the right of me.

00:14:48.649 --> 00:14:49.440
It was a community.

00:14:49.440 --> 00:14:52.190
The community actually
raised everyone.

00:14:52.190 --> 00:14:53.580
And it was always a barbershop.

00:14:53.580 --> 00:14:55.850
Like, Mr. Lewis and
always a barbecue joint.

00:14:55.850 --> 00:14:58.170
And like Mr. Reuben,
you know, like I

00:14:58.170 --> 00:15:00.660
don't know if you
noticed on the wall,

00:15:00.660 --> 00:15:02.940
it was like, he would
give kids free barbecue

00:15:02.940 --> 00:15:04.427
if he sees their report cards.

00:15:04.427 --> 00:15:05.010
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:15:05.010 --> 00:15:07.230
GEORGE TILLMAN: And
that's the kind of thing,

00:15:07.230 --> 00:15:09.550
that we want to
bring community back.

00:15:09.550 --> 00:15:13.000
One of the main things is
I love their relationship.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:16.360
It was very strong in the book,
between Mav and his daughter.

00:15:16.360 --> 00:15:17.620
And I thought that was great.

00:15:17.620 --> 00:15:19.630
And one of the
things I love to say

00:15:19.630 --> 00:15:24.140
is that the family
has so much joy in it.

00:15:24.140 --> 00:15:26.191
We have so many levels of humor.

00:15:26.191 --> 00:15:28.482
Believe it or not, there's
a lot of humor in the movie.

00:15:28.482 --> 00:15:28.860
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:15:28.860 --> 00:15:29.600
There really is.

00:15:29.600 --> 00:15:30.392
Don't get us wrong.

00:15:30.392 --> 00:15:32.850
GEORGE TILLMAN: There'll be a
lot of emotion, and it's fun.

00:15:32.850 --> 00:15:34.090
You will be entertained.

00:15:34.090 --> 00:15:37.130
But it's just issues
that we see every day.

00:15:37.130 --> 00:15:42.020
And I really do believe that the
film is an entertaining venue.

00:15:42.020 --> 00:15:44.110
That's why people pay
to go see movies--

00:15:44.110 --> 00:15:44.980
to be entertained.

00:15:44.980 --> 00:15:47.438
But the movie has that, but
you'll be able to relate to it,

00:15:47.438 --> 00:15:49.420
because there's the family.

00:15:49.420 --> 00:15:51.040
And no matter all
these obstacles,

00:15:51.040 --> 00:15:52.976
they keep pushing through.

00:15:52.976 --> 00:15:54.100
They keep going through it.

00:15:54.100 --> 00:15:55.900
And at end, we see
Starr has her journey.

00:15:55.900 --> 00:15:58.025
And that's the main thing
that I'm really proud of,

00:15:58.025 --> 00:15:59.770
that it was two parents.

00:15:59.770 --> 00:16:01.460
They're very close.

00:16:01.460 --> 00:16:02.290
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:16:02.290 --> 00:16:04.317
GEORGE TILLMAN: They
talk about sex a lot.

00:16:04.317 --> 00:16:04.900
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:16:04.900 --> 00:16:06.970
There really is, like,
a romantic relationship

00:16:06.970 --> 00:16:08.100
that grounds them.

00:16:08.100 --> 00:16:09.100
GEORGE TILLMAN: Yeah, it
grounds them together.

00:16:09.100 --> 00:16:10.390
SPEAKER: They're like,
there's my parent.

00:16:10.390 --> 00:16:12.139
GEORGE TILLMAN: I just
had some memories--

00:16:12.139 --> 00:16:13.690
I just had memories
when I was-- we

00:16:13.690 --> 00:16:15.970
were doing a scene
in the diner, and how

00:16:15.970 --> 00:16:17.980
the family, after
this big incident,

00:16:17.980 --> 00:16:20.950
the family just closed their
hands again, and they prayed.

00:16:20.950 --> 00:16:22.900
So to me, that was a
throwback to soul food,

00:16:22.900 --> 00:16:25.727
around the dinner table,
and the food, and every--

00:16:25.727 --> 00:16:27.310
And I'd even tell
the actors to do it.

00:16:27.310 --> 00:16:30.400
Everybody just started
overlapping, talking

00:16:30.400 --> 00:16:32.470
dialogue, talking about
food, eat that hot sauce,

00:16:32.470 --> 00:16:33.820
don't put the hot sauce
on that, you better

00:16:33.820 --> 00:16:34.920
get to those vegetables first.

00:16:34.920 --> 00:16:36.867
All that was just, we
were family at the time.

00:16:36.867 --> 00:16:37.450
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:16:37.450 --> 00:16:37.870
GEORGE TILLMAN: Yeah.

00:16:37.870 --> 00:16:39.661
SPEAKER: And that's
what makes for a really

00:16:39.661 --> 00:16:41.180
authentic storytelling, too.

00:16:41.180 --> 00:16:44.380
And you mentioned the fun,
and the joy, and the humor,

00:16:44.380 --> 00:16:47.170
and a lot of the things
you were shooting.

00:16:47.170 --> 00:16:50.000
How did you guys
maintain a sense of joy?

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:53.380
You know, I feel like black
joy and black excellence,

00:16:53.380 --> 00:16:56.762
black happiness, is so
important in terms of self-care.

00:16:56.762 --> 00:16:58.720
So like, even when you're
shooting a scene that

00:16:58.720 --> 00:17:02.740
is so heavy, that's
emotionally charged,

00:17:02.740 --> 00:17:04.510
how do you guys kind
of come back and find

00:17:04.510 --> 00:17:05.925
the joy in what you're doing?

00:17:05.925 --> 00:17:08.050
AMANDLA STENBERG: Well, we
have Regina Hall on set.

00:17:08.050 --> 00:17:09.949
SPEAKER: Right?

00:17:09.949 --> 00:17:11.240
AMANDLA STENBERG: She is a gem.

00:17:11.240 --> 00:17:12.157
SPEAKER: Oh, goodness.

00:17:12.157 --> 00:17:13.781
AMANDLA STENBERG:
Man, she's hilarious.

00:17:13.781 --> 00:17:15.010
She always brought the joy.

00:17:15.010 --> 00:17:17.680
Always brought the humor.

00:17:17.680 --> 00:17:19.930
I think is just our
natural inclination

00:17:19.930 --> 00:17:22.359
to work through trauma
that way, to rely

00:17:22.359 --> 00:17:26.920
upon our humor and our joy,
and even though this experience

00:17:26.920 --> 00:17:31.330
was so intense and
traumatic at times,

00:17:31.330 --> 00:17:33.040
there was always
a sense of levity,

00:17:33.040 --> 00:17:36.460
and like always a sense
of community and family,

00:17:36.460 --> 00:17:40.900
and a feeling that if you really
were coming up against a wall

00:17:40.900 --> 00:17:46.630
emotionally, and you were tired,
and these events and portraying

00:17:46.630 --> 00:17:49.000
them feel so heavy,
there is always

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:51.420
someone you could turn to
who would have your back.

00:17:51.420 --> 00:17:53.650
SPEAKER: That's community
at its very finest.

00:17:53.650 --> 00:17:56.530
And kind of having a nice
family to shoot with, really

00:17:56.530 --> 00:17:57.810
helps with that kind of thing.

00:17:57.810 --> 00:17:58.691
GEORGE TILLMAN: Yep.

00:17:58.691 --> 00:18:01.107
SPEAKER: Talking a little bit
more about having, you know,

00:18:01.107 --> 00:18:02.920
having that community
and that family all

00:18:02.920 --> 00:18:06.840
around you on set,
in the movie, I

00:18:06.840 --> 00:18:09.490
guess Starr is trying to figure
out who her community is,

00:18:09.490 --> 00:18:10.890
even outside of her home.

00:18:10.890 --> 00:18:13.540
So, in her school at Williamson.

00:18:13.540 --> 00:18:14.710
Chris is a great character.

00:18:14.710 --> 00:18:16.450
He's really interesting,
because he's

00:18:16.450 --> 00:18:19.600
navigating allyship,
and trying to figure out

00:18:19.600 --> 00:18:22.690
what that means for him, how
he fits into the scene, how

00:18:22.690 --> 00:18:25.960
he fits into Starr's life.

00:18:25.960 --> 00:18:30.310
If you guys had to, I guess,
determine something that's

00:18:30.310 --> 00:18:33.070
important for someone who
is trying to become an ally,

00:18:33.070 --> 00:18:36.010
or trying to figure out how they
can get involved in movements

00:18:36.010 --> 00:18:38.230
and civil rights
and racial equality,

00:18:38.230 --> 00:18:39.710
what's the first step?

00:18:39.710 --> 00:18:41.380
You know, it can
feel heavy, right,

00:18:41.380 --> 00:18:43.780
to step into a world you're
not used to, and be like,

00:18:43.780 --> 00:18:44.680
you know what?

00:18:44.680 --> 00:18:46.220
I'm with them.

00:18:46.220 --> 00:18:48.337
How do you do that?

00:18:48.337 --> 00:18:50.170
AMANDLA STENBERG: One
of my favorite lines--

00:18:50.170 --> 00:18:53.710
when I read it in the script,
I had this feeling of like,

00:18:53.710 --> 00:18:55.650
retribution of like,
oh, my god, I wish

00:18:55.650 --> 00:18:56.900
I had had this in high school.

00:18:56.900 --> 00:19:00.190
It would've have saved me so
much like, internal strife.

00:19:00.190 --> 00:19:04.810
But there's this scene
where Chris says to Starr,

00:19:04.810 --> 00:19:05.960
I don't see color.

00:19:05.960 --> 00:19:07.664
I just see a person
for who they are.

00:19:07.664 --> 00:19:08.330
Like, I see you.

00:19:08.330 --> 00:19:09.520
SPEAKER: Yes, yes.

00:19:09.520 --> 00:19:10.895
AMANDLA STENBERG:
And Starr says,

00:19:10.895 --> 00:19:12.987
if you don't see my
blackness, you don't see me.

00:19:12.987 --> 00:19:13.570
SPEAKER: Amen.

00:19:13.570 --> 00:19:15.850
AMANDLA STENBERG:
And that was so

00:19:15.850 --> 00:19:18.310
validating to read on the page.

00:19:18.310 --> 00:19:20.470
Because I think there's
this idea that in order

00:19:20.470 --> 00:19:25.390
to be an ally, you have to
look at the other person

00:19:25.390 --> 00:19:26.610
as your equal.

00:19:26.610 --> 00:19:29.200
But almost as if in the
process of doing that, in order

00:19:29.200 --> 00:19:31.900
to do that, you have to
discredit the aspects of them

00:19:31.900 --> 00:19:34.420
that are different,
or that make them

00:19:34.420 --> 00:19:38.830
more marginalized than
you, when really it

00:19:38.830 --> 00:19:40.120
should be the opposite.

00:19:40.120 --> 00:19:43.330
When you look at someone you
want to be an ally to them,

00:19:43.330 --> 00:19:46.750
it's so important that you are
inclusive of all the aspects

00:19:46.750 --> 00:19:49.350
of their identity
that make them them,

00:19:49.350 --> 00:19:54.520
and see them in the way in
which those aspects of self

00:19:54.520 --> 00:19:57.970
dictate or influence
their experience.

00:19:57.970 --> 00:20:01.270
Because the idea of, oh, I don't
see color is, like, really,

00:20:01.270 --> 00:20:02.819
like, it's a great intention.

00:20:02.819 --> 00:20:03.610
SPEAKER: Of course.

00:20:03.610 --> 00:20:04.735
AMANDLA STENBERG: For sure.

00:20:04.735 --> 00:20:07.570
But it also like, rests
upon the assumption

00:20:07.570 --> 00:20:11.575
that we live in a post-racial,
post-identity society.

00:20:11.575 --> 00:20:13.116
And we all know that
that's not true.

00:20:13.116 --> 00:20:14.050
SPEAKER: Which we would love.

00:20:14.050 --> 00:20:15.591
AMANDLA STENBERG:
We would love that,

00:20:15.591 --> 00:20:16.880
but that's not where we're at.

00:20:16.880 --> 00:20:18.588
I don't even know if
it's possible for us

00:20:18.588 --> 00:20:23.780
to be in a place that
doesn't use identity

00:20:23.780 --> 00:20:26.640
as a lens through which we
primarily look at each other.

00:20:26.640 --> 00:20:33.280
So I think being an ally
is about looking at someone

00:20:33.280 --> 00:20:38.360
and not being afraid of the
discomfort, of, oh, this person

00:20:38.360 --> 00:20:40.040
is different than me.

00:20:40.040 --> 00:20:42.590
Their experience
different than me.

00:20:42.590 --> 00:20:46.760
It's not about
trying to postulate

00:20:46.760 --> 00:20:48.950
their experience
as equal to yours,

00:20:48.950 --> 00:20:51.900
but rather like respecting it,
and all of its differences.

00:20:51.900 --> 00:20:52.727
SPEAKER: Accepting.

00:20:52.727 --> 00:20:53.310
Learning from.

00:20:53.310 --> 00:20:53.570
AMANDLA STENBERG: Yeah.

00:20:53.570 --> 00:20:54.810
And learning about it.

00:20:54.810 --> 00:20:56.226
And I really think
sometimes, it's

00:20:56.226 --> 00:20:57.412
just is about shutting up--

00:20:57.412 --> 00:20:59.120
sitting down, shutting
up, and listening.

00:20:59.120 --> 00:21:00.222
SPEAKER: Open those ears.

00:21:00.222 --> 00:21:01.180
AMANDLA STENBERG: Yeah.

00:21:01.180 --> 00:21:04.660
Because I think that's
what is really, you know--

00:21:04.660 --> 00:21:07.400
when there's a group of
people who have historically

00:21:07.400 --> 00:21:10.430
taken up a space and been
very comfortable in that,

00:21:10.430 --> 00:21:13.610
it is very uncomfortable to
no longer take up that space,

00:21:13.610 --> 00:21:18.790
or control it, or kind of demand
that you take up most of it.

00:21:18.790 --> 00:21:23.150
And so, what looks
like discomfort

00:21:23.150 --> 00:21:25.800
to people who have
historically had

00:21:25.800 --> 00:21:30.830
privilege is often just equity.

00:21:30.830 --> 00:21:33.410
That's what's really
essential for Chris

00:21:33.410 --> 00:21:38.210
to understand, is he needs
to take a step back and not

00:21:38.210 --> 00:21:41.870
take up as much space, even
in their conversations.

00:21:41.870 --> 00:21:42.800
SPEAKER: Right.

00:21:42.800 --> 00:21:45.590
AMANDLA STENBERG: Starr is
really assertive in making sure

00:21:45.590 --> 00:21:48.830
that he's listening to
her and saying, actually,

00:21:48.830 --> 00:21:50.690
this is my time to talk.

00:21:50.690 --> 00:21:51.530
And listen to me.

00:21:51.530 --> 00:21:52.370
SPEAKER: Here's my story.

00:21:52.370 --> 00:21:53.260
AMANDLA STENBERG:
Here's my story.

00:21:53.260 --> 00:21:55.310
And so, I think that's
a huge part of it,

00:21:55.310 --> 00:21:58.160
is stepping back and
being like, oh, I'm

00:21:58.160 --> 00:22:01.340
so used to taking up all
this space right here.

00:22:01.340 --> 00:22:03.720
But, actually, let me step back.

00:22:03.720 --> 00:22:07.000
I mean, draw it back in
and allow this other person

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:10.400
the time and the space.

00:22:10.400 --> 00:22:11.700
I'm using the word space a lot.

00:22:11.700 --> 00:22:15.127
The time and the space
to express themselves.

00:22:15.127 --> 00:22:15.710
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:22:15.710 --> 00:22:17.850
AMANDLA STENBERG: And
express their perspective.

00:22:17.850 --> 00:22:18.410
GEORGE TILLMAN: Yeah.

00:22:18.410 --> 00:22:19.490
There's like, two people--

00:22:19.490 --> 00:22:21.239
there's two lines in
the movie that define

00:22:21.239 --> 00:22:23.420
that, how an ally can work.

00:22:23.420 --> 00:22:28.400
Sabrina Carpenter plays Hailey.

00:22:28.400 --> 00:22:31.486
And she says, who else is going
to speak up for people, girl?

00:22:31.486 --> 00:22:33.920
And she's a white
individual saying that.

00:22:33.920 --> 00:22:35.512
And then you got--

00:22:35.512 --> 00:22:36.470
SPEAKER: Shook my core.

00:22:36.470 --> 00:22:37.345
GEORGE TILLMAN: Yeah.

00:22:37.345 --> 00:22:38.900
You got K.J. Apa
who plays Chris,

00:22:38.900 --> 00:22:43.200
and his line is, being an ally,
what do you want me to do?

00:22:43.200 --> 00:22:44.360
What do you want me--

00:22:44.360 --> 00:22:45.357
how can I help?

00:22:45.357 --> 00:22:46.190
SPEAKER: Absolutely.

00:22:46.190 --> 00:22:48.731
GEORGE TILLMAN: So that shows
the difference between the two,

00:22:48.731 --> 00:22:50.510
that we show two
different sides.

00:22:50.510 --> 00:22:54.290
One is about listening instead
of trying to follow somebody.

00:22:54.290 --> 00:22:54.890
So--

00:22:54.890 --> 00:22:55.840
SPEAKER: Being a part of it.

00:22:55.840 --> 00:22:56.780
GEORGE TILLMAN: Yeah.

00:22:56.780 --> 00:22:58.880
SPEAKER: So one thing
that's really interesting

00:22:58.880 --> 00:23:01.910
is, you know, as Starr is trying
to figure out whether or not

00:23:01.910 --> 00:23:04.760
she's going to use her
voice and speak up,

00:23:04.760 --> 00:23:08.000
I mean, we see that happening
in different ways in the world

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:09.630
now with, like,
hashtag activism.

00:23:09.630 --> 00:23:10.130
Right?

00:23:10.130 --> 00:23:13.040
So it's incredible that
we're using social media

00:23:13.040 --> 00:23:15.830
to say their names
and to learn more

00:23:15.830 --> 00:23:19.900
about the stories that aren't
really being told without it.

00:23:19.900 --> 00:23:21.650
But then bringing that
into the real world

00:23:21.650 --> 00:23:23.450
and taking another
step is very different.

00:23:23.450 --> 00:23:26.630
So what advice do
you have for people

00:23:26.630 --> 00:23:30.579
who are yearning to speak
out, who want to speak out,

00:23:30.579 --> 00:23:32.120
who want to try and
do something new,

00:23:32.120 --> 00:23:35.780
but are kind of feeling that
little bit of them that's

00:23:35.780 --> 00:23:36.870
holding them back?

00:23:36.870 --> 00:23:39.120
What's the first step
to opening yourself up

00:23:39.120 --> 00:23:40.370
to trying something like that?

00:23:44.964 --> 00:23:46.130
AMANDLA STENBERG: I really--

00:23:46.130 --> 00:23:49.010
